## 5. Existing direct-immediate event producers

These explicitly set `immediateTelegram: true` or `level: fatal`, so they can page Telegram without waiting for an agent response:

| Producer | File:line | Content |
|---|---|---|
| CLI/SDK high or urgent notification | `packages/sdk/src/capabilities/adapters/gateway-redis.ts:153-157` | Arbitrary operator notification |
| Restate high/urgent notification | `packages/restate/src/otel.ts:105-123` | DAG failure |
| Gateway health failure | `packages/system-bus/src/inngest/functions/check-gateway-health.ts:725` | Infra alert |
| OTEL error-rate alert | `packages/system-bus/src/inngest/functions/check-system-health.ts:1665` | Infra alert |
| Memory write-gate drift | `packages/system-bus/src/inngest/functions/check-system-health.ts:1705` | Probe/drift alert |
| Fatal system health | `packages/system-bus/src/inngest/functions/check-system-health.ts:1873` | Infra alert |
| O11y triage | `packages/system-bus/src/inngest/functions/o11y-triage.ts:861-887` | Investigated escalation |
| Slack mention approval | `packages/gateway/src/channels/slack.ts:181` | Joel-owned approval |
| Slack Reply Grant receipt | `packages/gateway/src/channels/slack.ts:1369` | Action receipt |

Other `gateway.notify()` and `pushGatewayEvent()` producers first pass `classifyOperatorSignal()` and usually become a batched/immediate agent prompt. Their eventual Telegram output is attributed generically as `gateway-console-forward`, so the original producer is usually lost.

